This article first appeared in Africa Check. South Africaâ€™s COVID-19 state of disaster ended in late March 2022. The government is now looking to add some of the regulations used to manage the pandemic to existing law â€“ the National Health Act. The proposed changes are open for public comment until July. But controversy has not been far behind, and the amendments may be challenged in court. Scientists have also weighed in. The Democratic Alliance (DA), the official opposition to South Africaâ€™s ruling African National Congress, has also objected to the proposed regulations. In early April the party tweeted: â€œğŸš¨ How do you feel about forced COVID-19 vaccination? Don't let NDZ and the Minister of Health take away your power and normalise the State of Disaster!â€ NDZ is shorthand for Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma, minister of cooperative governance and often the public face of pandemic rules. Michele Clarke, DA shadow minister for health, told Africa Check that the proposed regulations would be introduced â€œin addition to the existing legislation and regulationsâ€, and would â€œinclude COVID-19 as a Notifiable Medical Conditionâ€. This would â€œallow the regulations to restrict and limit certain rights as well as force certain practices on those who test positive for COVID-19â€, Clarke said. Claims about what the proposed regulations entail have also been spreading on WhatsApp, Facebook  and Twitter. Africa Check recently debunked the claim that the regulations would override the right to privacy. In this analysis, we explain what the National Health Act is, and what the draft regulations would change. Background: the National Health Act The National Health Act (NHA), implemented in 2003, sets out laws that govern South Africaâ€™s health system. â€œIt is national legislation that covers the operation of several areas of what we classically deem the â€˜health sectorâ€™,â€ Petronell Kruger, senior researcher at the Wits University Centre for Health Economics and Decis